Patient two, a 17-year-old male, was first seen in our clinic in August 2009. He had a two year history of an increasing number of avascular slightly depressed porcelain like lesions with an erythematous rim, primarily on his chest and abdomen, with more scattered lesions on his limbs, but none on his head, back or genitalia. Biopsy of a truncal lesion was consistent with a diagnosis of MAP (Additional file
). He had no clinical or serologic findings to suggest overlap with any connective tissue disorder. Colonoscopy revealed a limited number of similar appearing lesions on the bowel wall. Within a few months, he started to experience episodes of crampy abdominal pain. These increased in frequency and intensity and he developed an acute abdomen in December 2009. At laparotomy, the serosa of the small bowel revealed hundreds of lesions consistent with MAP (Additional file
). He had peritoneal fluid with polymicrobial growth but no area of bowel perforation was identified. He was treated with broad spectrum antibiotic therapy but redeveloped evidence of acute abdomen and required re-exploration 10 days later. He was found to have edematous and ischemic appearing loops of bowl with “abdominal compartment syndrome;” but again, no frank perforation. The abdominal wound was left open. He remained febrile, hypertensive, and tachycardic. He was treated with IV eculizumab based on successful use of this agent in a patient similarly afflicted
[-]. Almost immediate improvement was noted, with resolution of fever and tachycardia and a decrease in swelling of the bowel loops. On continued eculizumab, he had sustained improvement and the abdominal wound was successfully closed after another 10 days.
He was able to return to school within two months without abdominal pain.
Despite continued eculizumab therapy, by late 2010 he had redeveloped bouts of abdominal pain and he had developed gross hematuria with cystoscopy showing lesions suspicious for MAP. The abdominal pain was of such severity as to require bowel

